# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acaçá
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acaçá/acaca] Acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC) is a complex multifunctional enzyme system.
[src:acaçá/acaca] ACC is a biotin-containing enzyme which catalyzes the carboxylation of acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA, the rate-limiting step in fatty acid synthesis.
[src:acaçá/acaca] There are two ACC forms, alpha and beta, encoded by two different genes.
[src:acaçá/acaca] ACC-alpha is highly enriched in lipogenic tissues.
[src:acaçá/acaca] The enzyme is under long term control at the transcriptional and translational levels and under short term regulation by the phosphorylation/dephosphorylation of targeted serine residues and by allosteric transformation by citrate or palmitoyl-CoA.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Acaçá is the only ritual food required in Candomblé; it is offered to all the orixás in the Candomblé pantheon.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Acaçá made of white corn is offered to Oxala; that made of yellow corn is offered to Oxossi.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Acaçá is made of white or red corn soaked in water for a day, which is then passed through a mill to make a paste or dough.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] The paste or dough is cooked in a pan and stirred continuously to reach a correct consistency.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] While warm, small portions of the dough are wrapped in a clean, folded clean banana leaf and passed over a fire.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Finely ground white cornmeal can be substituted for soaked corn.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] The acaçá is cut into pieces of equal size.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] They are arranged on a platter to be placed on or near a *pegi*, or Candomblé altar.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] They also decorate other ritual foods in Candomblé, notably vatapá.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto (Portuguese: *acaçá of black beans*) is a variation of the acaçá made from black beans, i.e., the black turtle bean (*Phaseolus vulgaris*).
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Black beans are substituted for soaked corn, similarly made into a paste, wrapped in banana leaves, and steamed in a pan.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto is specifically offered to the god Ogum.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] The variation of acaçá is associated with Casa Fanti Ashanti, a Candomblé temple of the Jeje-Nagô tradition in the neighborhood of Cruzeiro do Anil, São Luís, in the state of Maranhão.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Acaçá de leite (transl. acaçá of milk) is a fermented drink used in Candomblé rituals.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] It is made from a corn mush to which milk and other seasonings are added.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] Acaçá de leite is found in Candomblé temples in Bahia and the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] A variation, acaçá de leite de coco, is made from coconut milk.
[src:acaçá/acaçá] This variation is found in the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:acaçá/alivenci] A form of cheesecake was very popular in Ancient Greece.
[src:acaçá/alivenci] The secret of its manufacture was passed during the Roman invasions.
[src:acaçá/alivenci] At that time, the Latin name used for this type of cake was placenta that was transmitted in Romanian culture.
[src:acaçá/alivenci] For Saint Peter, the Moldovan prepare alivenci.
[src:acaçá/amylomaize] Amylomaize starch is principally used in making biodegradable plastics (or bioplastics).
[src:acaçá/amylomaize] It is also used in edible and digestible coatings.
[src:acaçá/amylomaize] The food consumed on Apollo space flights from 1969 to 1972 were coated with an amylomaize film to prevent crumbs from floating around the space capsule.
[src:acaçá/amylomaize] Bear had discovered and reported that waxy corn (100% amylopectin starch) also occurred as a mutation.
[src:acaçá/amylomaize] Once discovered and reported, waxy mutations were found in the order of once every 30,000 observations.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Arepa can be served with accompaniments, such as cheese, *cuajada*, various types of meat, avocado, or *diablito* (deviled ham spread).
[src:acaçá/arepa] It can also be split to make sandwiches.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Sizes, maize types, and added ingredients vary based on preparation.
[src:acaçá/arepa] It is similar to the Mexican *gordita,* the Salvadoran pupusa, the Ecuadorian *tortilla de maíz*, and the Panamanian *tortilla* or *changa*.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The *arepa* is a pre-Columbian dish from the area that is now Colombia, Panama and Venezuela.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Instruments used to make flour for the *arepas*, and the clay slabs on which they were cooked, were often found at archaeological sites in the area.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Although it has not been specified in which country an **arepa** was cooked for the first time, it has been possible to define the oldest dates of the presence of maize in Colombia and Venezuela.
[src:acaçá/arepa] For example, in Colombia, the first record of the presence of corn cultivation dates from about 6,000 years ago.
[src:acaçá/arepa] However, the presence of arepas dates from 3,000 years ago (specifically in the Altiplano Cundiboyacense by the Muisca), while in Venezuela, the estimate is about 2,800 years ago.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Throughout its history, the **arepa** has stayed mainly unchanged from the **arepas** that pre-Columbian native peoples would have consumed, making the **arepa** one of the few pre-contact traditions that have remained popular in the years since colonization.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The name **arepa** is related to *erepa*, the word for 'cornbread' in the Cumanagoto language.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The **arepa** is a flat, round, unleavened patty of soaked, ground kernels of maize, or—more frequently nowadays—maize meal or maize flour.
[src:acaçá/arepa] It can be grilled, baked, fried, boiled, or steamed.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The characteristics vary by color, flavor, size, and the food with which it may be stuffed, depending on the region.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Simple **arepas** are filled with butter or cheese and baked.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Depending on the meal, more filling varieties can be added with combinations of ingredients like beans, meat, avocados, eggs, tomatoes, salad, shrimp, or fish.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Fried **arepas** are often consumed in northern South America, filled with white cheese on top and served with fried eggs.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Sweet fried **arepas** are another variety often prepared with sugarloaf (*papelón*) and anise (*anís*).
[src:acaçá/arepa] Venezuelan white cheese is another topping for fried *arepas* that can be combined with feta cheese.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Initially, *arepa* flour was made by grinding maize at home.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In the 1950s, precooked *arepa* flour was invented by Dr.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Luis Caballero Mejías, a Venezuelan engineer, and became an instant success.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The flour is mixed with water and salt, and occasionally oil, butter, eggs or milk.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Because the flour is already cooked, the blend forms into patties easily.
[src:acaçá/arepa] After being kneaded and formed, the patties are fried, grilled, or baked.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Some varieties of *arepas* are made with "peeled" corn using the nixtamalization process; they are known as *arepa pelada*.
[src:acaçá/arepa] However, in countries such as Colombia, it is not common to reconstitute corn flour as it is in Venezuela.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Thus, in Colombia, it is more common to see pre-roasted arepas ready for consumption in stores and supermarkets, giving rise to an industry that in 2019 alone had sales of USD $124 million with companies such as Arepas Sary and Alpina Productos Alimenticios.
[src:acaçá/arepa] According to food anthropologist Ocarina Castillo of the Central University of Venezuela, the dish is likely thousands of years old and originated in the region now occupied by the two countries before colonizers of the area drew borders.
[src:acaçá/arepa] There are different ways to prepare *arepas*, but one of the most traditional is the Cotoca recipe.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Several varieties of *arepa* can be found in the country, such as the Cruceña and Andina varieties.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The first record of the existence of arepas dates from about 3,000 years ago in what is currently Colombia.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The *arepa* is an iconic food in Colombia, with some 75 distinct preparation forms.
[src:acaçá/arepa] According to a study conducted by the Colombian Academy of Gastronomy, the *arepa* is part of the Colombian cultural heritage and can be considered a symbol of national gastronomic unity.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In 2006, the *arepa* was named the cultural symbol of Colombia in a competition organized by *Semana* magazine with support from Caracol Televisión, the Ministry of Culture and 'Colombia is Passion'.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In the Paisa region, the *arepa* is especially important to the local people and sometimes accompanies all meals of the day.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In addition, *arepas* are strung into necklaces and placed around the necks of honored dignitaries as a sign of praise.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Many varieties of *arepa* were introduced from this region.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In Colombia, the *arepa* is sold commercially in neighborhood stores, chain supermarkets, and market plazas and packaged with preservatives as a pre-molded white or yellow corn dough ready to grill or fry at home.
[src:acaçá/arepa] It is also sold in the form of industrialized corn flour that requires hydration before preparation.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In addition, *arepas* are sold by street vendors, in cafeterias, and in neighborhood stores.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Restaurants of the Paisa Region offer a wide variety of *arepas*, including a unique style of stuffed *arepa* that can be filled with eggs, meat, or cheese.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Colombians in the Caribbean region commonly eat a breakfast variation called *arepa con huevo*, which consists of a cooked *arepa* which has been split open, stuffed with a raw egg, and fried.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The Colombian Arepa Festival is celebrated in Barranquilla, Bogotá, Bucaramanga, Cali and Medellín.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Each city takes turns organizing the festival between August and December.
[src:acaçá/arepa] There are also many other types of arepas, including arepa de choclo, arepa de queso, arepa frita, arepa costeña, arepa de yuca, and arepa paisa.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Some recipes for this type of **arepa** can contain *doble crema* cheese and chicken.
[src:acaçá/arepa] One of its characteristics is that it is relatively thin unlike other *arepas* and also has a toasted and golden colored shell.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Another variation is the **arepa* boyacense*, with the Municipality of Ventaquemada being one of the most outstanding in terms of its production.
[src:acaçá/arepa] This type of **arepa** may contain butter, eggs, and cheese.
[src:acaçá/arepa] It has a certain sweetness, and in some recipes, this **arepa** may have *cuajada*.
[src:acaçá/arepa] There is also the **arepa* paisa*, which is consumed in the Department of Antioquia.
[src:acaçá/arepa] It is prepared with *maíz trillado* (lit.
[src:acaçá/arepa] This form most closely resembles indigenous cuisine.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In addition, another **arepa** variation consumed in the Andean region of the country is the **arepa* santandereana*, which contains cooked yuca and *chicharrón*.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In the Province of Guanacaste, **arepas** are prepared in the form of large, toasted sponge cakes, seasoned with *Bagaces* type cheese.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In Cartago, during colonial times, *arepas* were filled with pork.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In Puerto Rico, mainly in the San Juan area and beach sides, *arepas* are popular.
[src:acaçá/arepa] They can also be found in some restaurants, almost always as *arepas de coco*.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The Puerto Rican *arepa* is made with wheat flour, coconut milk, coconut oil, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:acaçá/arepa] They can be fried, baked, or cooked on a grill.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Once done, the *arepa* is cut open and stuffed.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Crab, shrimp, and octopus stewed in sofrito, lemon, coconut milk, and ginger, among other ingredients, are the most popular.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The arepa is a symbol of Venezuelan gastronomy and one of the most common pre-Hispanic foods still popular in Venezuela.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The first records of this dish are about 2,800 years ago.
[src:acaçá/arepa] According to a 2015 survey of the Venezuelan people, nearly 70 percent of the nation ate **arepas** regularly.
[src:acaçá/arepa] It is common for Venezuelans to eat **arepas** throughout the day, both as snacks and as sides to meals, creating a culture where these corn products (Harina PAN) can be found almost everywhere and in specific restaurants called *areperas*.
[src:acaçá/arepa] The **arepa** is seen as a cornerstone of a Venezuelan diet; prior to the 2015 food shortages, it was estimated that each year the average Venezuelan consumed about 30 kilos of the corn flour used to make **arepas**.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Venezuelan *arepas* are commonly filled with a great variety of different fillings, from beef and avocado to cheese, varying widely by the location of where they are sold and the ingredients that can be obtained.
[src:acaçá/arepa] In Venezuela's Andes region, *arepas de trigo* are made with wheat flour rather than cornmeal.
[src:acaçá/arepa] These lighter **arepas** are generally eaten as a snack or an accompaniment to heavier meals.
[src:acaçá/arepa] Former Venezuelan president Nicolás Maduro "has tried to use arepas as a nationalist rallying point, if not a political tool, claiming the food is from his country alone", according to the *New York Times*.
[src:acaçá/atole] Many Classic Maya painted vessels feature a genre of inscriptions known as the "dedicatory formula" or the "primary standard sequence" (PSS) and the two main ingredients mentioned in the contents section of the PSS were cacao and atole.
[src:acaçá/atole] In Mexico, the drink typically includes *masa* (corn hominy flour), water, *piloncillo* (unrefined cane sugar), cinnamon, vanilla, and optional chocolate or fruit.
[src:acaçá/atole] The mixture is blended and heated before serving.
[src:acaçá/atole] *Atole* is made by toasting *masa* on a *comal* (griddle), then adding water that was boiled with cinnamon sticks.
[src:acaçá/atole] In Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador, and Nicaragua, *atol de elote* (maize *atol*), or simply *atole*, is a common beverage.
[src:acaçá/atole] Pineapple *atol* (*atol de piña*) is also consumed in El Salvador.
[src:acaçá/atole] Guatemalan varieties include *atol shuco* ("dirty" *atol*, a reference to its darker color), consumed particularly often in the city.
[src:acaçá/atole] In Guatemala, the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development provided funding to INCAP to carry out a community randomized trial to test the hypothesis that improved protein intakes lead to better child development test scores.
[src:acaçá/atole] They were given a high-protein atole-like beverage made from INCAPARINA (a vegetable protein mixture developed by INCAP which mainly contains corn), dry skim milk, sugar, and a flavoring agent.
[src:acaçá/atole] In New Mexico, blue corn *atole* is finely ground cornmeal toasted for cooking, consumed as a grainy porridge-style drink served warm, usually sweetened with sugar or thinned with milk.
[src:acaçá/atole] It is usually served at breakfast like Cream of Wheat or oatmeal.
[src:acaçá/atole] Elders are said to have drunk *atole* because it gave them energy.
[src:acaçá/atole] A mother who is nursing will drink *atole* to give her more milk.
[src:acaçá/atole] The Puebloan peoples of New Mexico sometimes call *atole* *chaquehue* or *chaquewa*.
[src:acaçá/atole] The Ancestral Puebloans began to cultivate corn around 2000 BCE, and used advanced irrigation ditches as early as 205 CE.
[src:acaçá/atole] Later, during the time of Spanish colonialization, blue corn was irrigated by Moorish-influenced acequia systems.
[src:acaçá/atole] The Hopi plant blue corn seeds in bundles of several seeds to one hole, sometimes quite deep to reach ground water.
[src:acaçá/atole] Atole porridge is called mush by the Diné, and includes the addition of juniper ash.
[src:acaçá/atole] Atole flour is used to create Hopi piki bread.
[src:acaçá/atole] The beverage is referenced in the Spanish idiom *dar atole con el dedo* ("to give *atole* with the thumb"), which means to placate with deception.
[src:acaçá/atole] It may originate from the idea of wet nurses using *atole* on their thumbs to placate infants; alternatively, it may refer to the practice of distributing tamales and *atole* during periods of drought in pre-Columbian Mexico.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] There are two methods for producing baby corn: either as a primary crop, or as a secondary crop in a planting of sweet corn or field corn.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] In the first method, a seed variety is chosen and planted to produce only baby corn.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] Many varieties are suitable, but those developed specifically for baby corn tend to produce more ears per plant.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] In the second production method, the variety is selected to produce sweet or field corn.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] The second ear from the top of the plant is harvested for baby corn, while the top ear is allowed to mature.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] Baby corn ears are hand-picked as soon as the corn silks emerge from the ear tips, or a few days after.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] Corn generally matures very quickly, so the harvest of baby corn must be timed carefully to avoid ending up with more mature corn ears.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] Baby corn production mostly occurs in Asia, as it is a specialized form of corn farming often requiring hand picking, which is generally not compatible with mechanized corn agriculture practiced in the United States.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] It is often associated with Chinese-American food, such as stir-fry, though it is not as widely used in China.
[src:acaçá/baby-corn] Baby corn forage can also be fed fresh or ensiled to livestock animals.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] In agronomy, the **BBCH-scale for cereals** describes the phenological development of cereals using the BBCH-scale.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] The **Feekes scale** is a system to identify the growth and development of cereal crops introduced by the Dutch agronomists Willem Feekes (1907-1979) in 1941.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] This scale is more widely used in the United States than other similar and more descriptive scales such as the Zadoks scale or the BBCH scale.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] Like other scales of crop development, the Feekes scale is useful in planning management strategies that incorporate plant growth information for the use of pesticides and fertilizers to avoid damaging the crop and/or maximize crop yield.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] The **Zadoks scale** is a cereal development scale proposed by the Dutch phytopathologist Jan Zadoks that is widely used in cereal research and agriculture.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] Knowing the stages of development of a crop is critical in many management decisions that growers make.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] They are represented on a scale from 10 to 92.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] For example, in some countries, nitrogen and herbicide applications must be completed during the tillering stage.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] In France, the recommendation for the first nitrogen application on wheat is 6 weeks before Z30, with the second application on Z30.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] Wheat growth regulators are typically applied at Z30.
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] Disease control is most critical in the stem extension and heading stage (Z31, Z32, Z35), in particular as soon as the flag leaf is out (Z37).
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] The crop is also more sensitive to heat or frost at some stages than others (for example, during the meiosis stage the crop is very sensitive to low temperature).
[src:acaçá/bbch-scale-maize] Knowing the growth stage of the crop when checking for problems is essential for deciding which control measures should be followed.
